ğŸ‡¨ğŸ‡² For many years I always thought this Cameroon shirt with a more angular interpretation of a lion on the front than the shirt I had already was not as nice and so ignored it. Over the years I've realised I was wrong and somehow this incarnation feels more African and cool, and I've been fortunate that the shirt is still widely available to correct my mistake of not buying when it was current. As always I love the double badge and centralised Puma logo... using them in the eye sockets of the lion is a masterstroke. The real beauty of this though is in the little dots running down the sleeve and used to make up the lion's face in a sort of Roy Lichtenstein homage which I'd never noticed either when I didn't rate the design, or when I'd come round to loving it. The Cameroon flag colours around the collar matches up nicely with the badges as well and just have no excuse as to why I wasn't in love with this from day one of its release. I missed Cameroon at the last World Cup after years of liking them but thinking I wouldn't miss them. I feel Cameroon were the archetypal African nation at a World Cup for anyone of my generation (don't comment to say it was Nigeria, you're wrong), and certainly the standard bearer for kit designs before kit design became important - whilst almlost every African nation is now kitted out magnificently every year, Cameroon were doing it before it sold. Here's hoping they're present in 2022, especially as Le Coq Sportif are making a decent effort at replacing Puma. #cameroon #cameroun #indomitablelions #afcon #africanfootball #africanfootballshirt #pumaafrica #puma #green #instagood #africannation #africa #internationalfooball #lion #football #footballshirt #footballshirts #footballshirtcollector #footballshirtcollection #trikot #jersey #camiseta #maillot #maillotdefoot #maglia #shirt #footballkit #footballkits #soccerjersey #kitcollector

One would say... Really... both tires flat , really... and yes that is the god damn reality of things.. I have no tubes lying around so couldn't use the bike to warm up for my long run today... and it is a bank holiday, so can't buy new ones today. 
Well nomatter, just had to run fairly slow until I got warmed up... 
Yesterday I had one hour bike and weight session, but skipped squat because I wanted to run 10+ today. 
I heard a podcast yesterday #atleterudenfilter by @louiburgaard , with a Danish marathon runner which reminded me, about something I already know but tend to forget. Training long distance run isn't about speed but about kilometers. So ran a 6.minute pace per km for 11k today.. instead of the 5.35 which I usually do, running that route... 
Once again I am sitting comparing myself with back then, when I trained for ironman, and once again I have to remind myself I am rebooting my training and I am nowhere near my former run pace and I don't need to be.. I train so I can do a half ironman. I wanna be in half ironman shape... Not to compete, not to be faster than my first half ironman... Just because I like the training and I wanna be able to, if I suddenly feel the urge to do a race... 
I simply just love the training.. Well once again it rained my whole run ğŸŒ§ but still...

Came across this family fun trail while hiking to my Elkmont campsite in the GSM. 

Want to include the entire family on a very exciting hiking trail that will reward you with some amazing views and have you away from the crowds?

Well look no further my friends as the Great Smoky Mountains NP has provided you with Clingmans Dome Bypass Trail! 

This Family Friendly trail has grades along this trail that will challenge children but their short durations make them doable, and the breathtaking views atop Clingmans Dome make them worth it.

The trailhead is located at the Clingmans Dome parking lot where the Forney Ridge Trail begins. While the paved trail to Clingmans Dome might be easier, it can be very crowded. If you are looking for solitude as you start your adventures on the AT, this is the quieter option for getting to the long trail. 

The Clingmans Dome Bypass Trail drops .2 miles from the parking lot before coming to a junction. The trail goes off to the right and begins to climb uphill towards the Appalachian Trail (AT). The trail is rocky through this section, but views of some high elevation meadows are offered on the left side of the trail. The tree cover quickly disappears due to the death of the Fraser firs in the area. The trail climbs gently until it meets up with the Appalachian Trail (AT) .3 miles west of Clingmans Dome observation tower. At this junction, excellent views of Elkmont and Sugarland Mountain are off to the north and west. 

Once you reach the junction, you have several options. Off to your left, you can explore the 

Appalachian Trail as it makes its way toward Silers Bald. If you turn to the right, you can follow the AT back to Clingmans Dome Observation Tower (and the crowds) and then follow the paved trail back to the parking lot. 

It's a 1.5 mile roundtrip loop, making for a nice day in the mountains.

Shared By: David Hitchcock
